1777	  in some chart \(U^I\) (\(\Spec K\) has one point), so it is given by a ring map
1778	  \(f : \mathbb{Z}[X^I] \to K\). Among the \(\binom{r}{d}\) minors choose \(J\)
1779	  with \(\nu(f(P^I_J))\) minimal. Because \(P^I_I = 1\) gives \(f(P^I_I) = 1\)
1780	  with \(\nu = 0\), the minimum satisfies \(\nu(f(P^I_J)) \le 0\); in particular
1781	  \(f(P^I_J) \ne 0\), so \(f(X^I_J) \in \mathrm{GL}_d(K)\) is invertible over
1782	  \(K\). Define
1783	  \[
1784	    g : \mathbb{Z}[X^J] \longrightarrow K, \qquad
1785	    g(X^J) = f\bigl((X^I_J)^{-1} X^I\bigr) ;
1786	  \]
1787	  this is the composite of \(\theta_{I,J}\) (\cref{def:gr_transition}) with
1788	  \(f\), so \(g\) defines the same \(K\)-point \(\varphi\), now exhibited as
1789	  landing in \(U^J\).
1790	
1791	  We show every entry \(g(x^J_{p,q})\) lies in \(R\), i.e.\ has \(\nu \ge 0\).
1792	  First, for any size-\(d\) subset \(K' \subseteq \{1,\dots,r\}\) the \(K'\)-minor
1793	  of \((X^I_J)^{-1} X^I\) is \((X^I_J)^{-1} X^I_{K'}\), so
1794	  \[
1795	    g(P^J_{K'}) = \det f\bigl((X^I_J)^{-1} X^I_{K'}\bigr)
1796	    = \frac{f(P^I_{K'})}{f(P^I_J)},
1797	    \qquad
1798	    \nu(g(P^J_{K'})) = \nu(f(P^I_{K'})) - \nu(f(P^I_J)) \ge 0
1799	  \]
1800	  by minimality of \(\nu(f(P^I_J))\). Now the \(J\)-minor \(X^J_J\) of \(X^J\) is
1801	  the identity, so by cofactor expansion each individual entry
1802	  \(x^J_{p,q}\) (with \(q \notin J\)) equals, up to sign, the minor
1803	  \(P^J_{K'}\) for \(K' = (J \setminus \{j_p\}) \cup \{q\}\) -- the \(d \times d\)
1804	  determinant obtained by replacing the \(p\)-th identity column of \(X^J_J\) by
1805	  the column \(q\). Hence \(\nu(g(x^J_{p,q})) = \nu(g(P^J_{K'})) \ge 0\) for all
1806	  entries, and the entries with \(q \in J\) are \(0\) or \(1\). Therefore
1807	  \(g(\mathbb{Z}[X^J]) \subseteq R\), so \(g\) factors uniquely as
1808	  \(\mathbb{Z}[X^J] \to R \hookrightarrow K\). The corresponding morphism
1809	  \(\Spec R \to U^J \hookrightarrow \mathrm{Gr}(r,d)\) restricts to \(\varphi\)
1810	  over \(\Spec K\) and lies over \(\Spec \mathbb{Z}\), providing the filler.
1811	
1812	  \emph{Uniqueness.} Any two fillers agree over the generic point \(\Spec K\)
1813	  and, \(\mathrm{Gr}(r,d)\) being separated over \(\mathbb{Z}\)
1814	  (\cref{lem:gr_separated}), two morphisms \(\Spec R \to \mathrm{Gr}(r,d)\)
1815	  agreeing on the schematically dense open \(\Spec K\) coincide. This verifies
1816	  the valuative criterion, so \(\pi : \mathrm{Gr}(r,d) \to \Spec \mathbb{Z}\) is
1817	  proper.
1818	\end{proof}
1819	
1820	\section{Out of scope}
1821	\label{sec:gr_out_of_scope}
1822	
1823	This chapter constructs the Grassmannian \emph{scheme} \(\mathrm{Gr}(r,d)\) over
1824	the absolute base \(\mathbb{Z}\) and establishes its smoothness, separatedness
1825	and properness. The following constructions are deferred to later chapters and
1826	are not treated here:
1827	\begin{itemize}
1828	  \item \textbf{The tautological/universal quotient} \(u : \mathcal{O}^{\oplus
1829	    r}_{\mathrm{Gr}(r,d)} \twoheadrightarrow \mathcal{U}\) and the determinant
1830	    line bundle \(\det \mathcal{U}\) with its Pl\"ucker embedding.
1831	  \item \textbf{The functor-of-points representability} of \(\mathrm{Gr}(r,d)\)
1832	    -- that it represents \(\mathrm{Grass}(r,d) =
1833	    \Quot^{d,\mathcal{O}_{\mathbb{Z}}}_{\oplus^r \mathcal{O}_{\mathbb{Z}} /
1834	    \mathbb{Z} / \mathbb{Z}}\); this is blueprinted as
1835	    \cref{thm:grassmannian_representable} in
1836	    \cref{chap:Picard_QuotScheme}.
1837	  \item \textbf{The relative version over a general base \(S\)} with a locally
1838	    free sheaf \(V\) of rank \(r\): the scheme \(\mathrm{Gr}_S(V,d)\) obtained by
1839	    base change and gluing over a trivialising cover of \(V\). The
1840	    absolute-over-\(\mathbb{Z}\) construction of this chapter is the input to
1841	    that base change.
1842	\end{itemize}
